post_text:
Parents of Seniors:

October 1st is quickly approaching, and that is the day the Financial Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) opens for all students attending/planning to attend college. The earlier it is completed, the better. Below is some very helpful information to review on what documents you need to fill out FAFSA, where to go, and what to do in special living circumstances.

We will be hosting individual virtual FAFSA help sessions with our seniors and their families led by the Eastern KY KHEAA Representative on October 1st. Students will receive sign up information next week on their Class of 2021 Google Classroom.

Our guidance office and Knox Promise Neighborhood are also working together to host workshops for various grades with KHEAA to talk more about financial aid, scholarships, KEES money, etc. throughout the year. Stay tuned!

post_text:
We hope this adjusted calendar can address some of the questions we are having regarding virtual vs. in-class instruction.

On yellow days, all students will be completely virtual and logging in for class from home.

On blue days, the Blue Team will be at school for classes, and the White Team will be learning from home virtually.

On white days, the White Team will be at school for classes, and the Blue Team will be learning from home virtually.

Red days are non-instructional days, so no school online or on-site.

From September 9th- September 28th, both teams will be completely virtual. Following September 28th, we have hopes to be able to implement our rotation schedule. Your student will either be in the classroom on their team color days, or will be logging in from home on the opposite color days. Monday-Friday we will be having instruction in some form for all of the students unless listed as a non-instructional day.

Barbourville Families,
We will begin calling on Monday to inform you of the rotation for your children. We know that it is important for childcare purposes that you know ASAP. Due to numerous guidelines, we cannot take requests. Please call the office beginning Friday if you have not received your call. We will not be giving information out over the phone until Friday should you have missed your call. Our hope is to touch base with each family. #BISPROUD #BISHealthyatSchool

Day One of our Virtual Kindercamp was all about Math Monday! Students were provided with their very own counting bears, sorting tray, and materials for flash cards and lead in a fun hands-on math game. This activity prompted students to learn and refresh sorting, patterns, adding, and subtracting skills!

Thank you to Early Childhood and Knox Promise Neighborhood for funding and hosting such a fun and educational camp for our Kinders!

post_text:
Victor Bingham is the Senior of the day.

“Victor is so friendly and so good to people. He treats everyone with kindness and respect. He's smart, funny, and unique, and he will surely be missed at BHS”- Mr. Simpson
“Victor was a pleasure to have in class. He always would do what was asked of him and provided comedic breaks when needed. I wish Victor the best in his next steps.”- Mr. Cox
These are just a few GREAT things some of Victor’s teachers had to say when asked about him. When you ask Victor what his favorite memory has been at BIS he said “Everything I have done with my friends, no matter how big or how small.” Victor has been on the Tennis since 10th grade and Academic Team since 3rd Grade. Victor has a 3.5 GPA and plans to attend the University of Pikeville to pursue a degree in psychology and minor in computer science. From all of us at BIS we want to wish Victor good luck in his future endeavors.

post_text:
Senior Peyton Mills Places Third at State Writing Competition

Peyton Mills took third place in the Kentucky Scenario Writing Competition. This event, part of the Future Problem Solving competitions hosted by KAAC, requires students to write a 1500 word short story set at least 20 years in the future connected to one of this year’s Future Problem Solving topics. The pieces are scored by various judges throughout the state. This is Peyton’s third win at the state level. His piece has been sent on for scoring at the international competition and results will be released later this summer.

Congratulations, Peyton!

Do you have an elementary student?

This is a great opportunity to hear a wonderful children’s author read her books live! Her books address common childhood issues such as sibling rivalry, tattling, being too attached to technology, and even more serious issues such as being a bully or grief over a lost loved one. It is important to continue to promote healthy lifestyles from home, even when that bag of chips is calling your name! Taking care of your body by eating well and exercising has tremendous benefits for your mental health as well!

Below are some fun things you can do with your children at home to encourage them to stay active. If you decide to do the scavenger hunt, post some pictures below in the comments!

Have a great weekend, and remember to stay #healthyathome!

post_text: Great job, Braden!
shared_text:
Jag KY is with Cathy Sue Smith and Pamela Tye Chafin at St. Jude Children's Research Hospital.
March 26 at 6:36 PM · Memphis, TN ·

Barbourville HS JAG KY junior student, Braden, is busy working on a virtual community service opportunity sending e-cards to critically ill children at St. Jude Children's Research Hospital in Memphis, Tennessee. BHS JAG KY students have sent 100+ e-cards this week! It's always good to think of others less fortunate, especially in the midst of national crisis. We hope these cards are putting smiles on little faces this week! Great job everyone! 🥰

Happy Wellness Wednesday, Tigers!

For our elementary students-completing schoolwork at home can sometimes be frustrating. You may miss your friends and your teacher. You may struggle with an assignment and feel like you just can't do it! Hop over to the Cosmic Kids Zen Den and learn how to deal with those naughty "I can't" monsters!

https://youtu.be/jzYtNWjQiK0

For our middle and high school students- Balancing NTI work and responsibilities at home can be difficult. This video explains what everyday mindfulness is, and how being aware of what is going on around you and inside of you can help make life more enjoyable and less stressful.

https://youtu.be/QTsUEOUaWpY

post_text:
Hailey Hembree is the Senior of the Day

“She makes me laugh quite often, which is a wonderful quality to have,” said Mr. Simpson. Mr. Cox said, “Hembree always steals my chair (although never without asking)! Pleasure to have in class.” These are just a few GREAT things some of Hailey’s teachers had to say when asked about her. If you see her in the hallway, she is always smiling and laughing. When I asked Hailey what her favorite memory has been at BIS, she said, “would have to be when Peyton Lawson brought his guitar to school and started playing. He did it multiple times, but every time we would all just listen to him and some of us would sing.”. She has a 3.2 GPA and plans to attend Somerset Community College to pursue her degree in cosmetology. Hailey just celebrated her big 18th birthday. From all of us at BIS, we want to wish you a happy birthday!!

post_text:
Senior of the Day
Emily Grace Jones

When I asked Grace what her favorite memory has been at BIS, she said “getting to play sports that I love with my teammates.” Grace is a part of the Varsity Basketball team, Varsity Softball team, and the Varsity Volleyball team. Coach Andy Hillard said, “Grace is a very consistent and trust worthy player. I could always count on her in any situation to step up when needed”. She has a 4.0 GPA and plans to attend Union College to pursue her degree in nursing. Grace will be celebrating her big 18th birthday in two days. From all of us at BIS, we want to wish you a happy early birthday!!

Rest assured that the trip will go on once safe to do so and the money you have paid will not be lost because we could not travel on our original dates.

Thanks for your patience. It is going to be a great trip!

post_text:
Barbourville Independent will be following the advice of Governor Andy Beshear and Interim Commissioner Kevin Brown by taking the necessary steps to ensure that our school community is safe and well.

Beginning Monday, March 16, we will be closed and will be offering alternative methods of instruction through Friday, April 3rd 2020. SPRING BREAK is April 6th-10th and these days will not be days that student have class assignments.

TOMORROW WE WILL HAVE SCHOOL. Students will be given papers to bring home that will explain the process to be used during these NTI days and will also include information to describe our plans to continue to provide meals for our students.
In addition, our Family Resource/Youth Service Center will continue the backpack program and will work to provide needed assistance to our families.

Please look for the letter to come home tomorrow and to be posted as well.

Parents, if you have had a change in your telephone number or email address, please send a note with the corrections to school tomorrow.

shared_text:
Ralph Halcomb
March 3 at 9:20 PM ·

Congrats to these Knox Co ATC students who competed today at The regional SkillsUSA Competition held at the Bell Co ATC.

Brandon Abner (BHS) took home 1st place in the Welding 2 competition while Cody Smith (KCHS) got 3rd. Welding 2 is for experienced welders.

Matthew Warren (KCHS) earned 2nd in the Welding 1 competition which is for new welding students.

Group picture, from left to right: Herman Hensley, Andrew Roach, Devan King, Dakota Barnes, Wesley Lawson, Matthew Warren, Tristan Yates, Cody Smith, Dylan Deaton, George Trosper, Waylon Messer, Brandon Abner

I Love Math Week has been a blast at BIS!

Grades Prek-12th decorated the halls in our "Math Mania Hallway" to show what their class is studying or why they love math. KHEAA Representative, Emily Bowman, also came to tie in math to college readiness for 8th grade with a KEES Money Jeopardy game. Following, today the students did amazing in the Math Vocabulary Parade. Tomorrow we will announce the winners of our class Math Challenges, so stay tuned! BIS loves Math!

Middle School Academic Team Brings Home the Hardware at Regional Academic Tournament

The middle school academic team won four trophies at today’s regional Governor’s Cup Tournament. They placed 3rd in Quick Recall, 3rd in Future Problem Solving, and 4th Overall. They were also awarded the Hume Sportsmanship Award, awarded for displaying the best sportsmanship throughout the competition voted on by the competing teams.

Individual winners include: Savannah Hoffman—2nd Place Written Composition
Samuel Moore—4th Place Language Arts & 4th Place Arts & Humanities.

Both students will advance to the state competition in Louisville next month.

Congratulations to all our students on a job well done!

post_text:
Seventh Graders Qualify for Prestigious Duke Tip Talent Search Program

Barbourville Independent is proud to boast twenty-four students who qualified for the Duke Tip Seventh Grade Talent Search. Students qualify for the talent search by ranking in the top five percent in the nation on standardized testing in one subject area or in the top 10 percent in two or more areas. These students have the opportunity to take the ACT or SAT in February or March, respectively, to earn additional recognition at the state awards ceremony at Western Kentucky University in May.

Parents or Guardians--If your child is pictured, please be sure to complete the online registration process by Friday, January 17th, if you would like your child to be included in the program and take the ACT in February. A paper with details pertaining to the program and registration was sent home with each student today. There is a fee associated with registration which covers the ACT or SAT testing fee as well as other program perks.

Congratulations to all our qualifiers!

Not pictured: Abigail Mills

post_text:
AP Bio Students Investigate “McMush”

AP Bio students wrapped up their biochemistry unit by determining the biomolecules present in various menu items from a local restaurant. The foods were blended into “McMush” prior to the start of the lab. The students then tested each mixture using various chemical indicators for the presence of proteins, lipids, and carbohydrates. The lab was a huge “McHit” even though a few students admitted they got a little “McNauseous”.

Beta Club NYC Trip Payment #2 Now Due

The second $150 payment is now due for the New York City trip. Please submit your payment before Christmas break as the money will be used to purchase our "Wicked" broadway show tickets and Yankees game tickets. Please make payments next week, Tuesday--Friday. All payments should be turned in to Beta club sponsor Marsha Hubbs at the main office.

We have approximately 10 remaining spots available. These spots are open to middle and high school Beta club students and their families. Spots are given out as payments are made. A parent or guardian is NOT required to attend with each student, however, they are more than welcome! It's going to be a great trip!

post_text:
Governor's School for Entrepreneurs Application Now Open--Deadline 1/20/20

GSE is a three week residential summer program where young entrepreneurs, working in teams, take an idea and utilize STEAM and enterprise skills to create a service or product. Teams build a feasible business model around their idea. On the final day of the program, teams pitch their business idea to a live audience and panel of judges, known as Demo Day.

Interested? This program is free of charge and is open to students currently in grades 9, 10, or 11. See the website below for more details.

https://www.kentuckygse.com/

The BHS Junior Class will be hosting Daniel Boone Festival Bingo again this year! Local businesses, community organizations, or political candidates who would like to sponsor a Bingo Jackpot are encouraged to contact junior class sponsors, Marcia Dixon or Marsha Hubbs at 546-3129 or stop by bingo at the fire department Wednesday thru Saturday, 5:00 pm to 10:30 pm. Jackpot sponsors are given the option to call the bingo game they sponsor. All money raised during bingo supports the junior class in paying for prom and senior activities.
